Solution. 1) The given function is a product of power functions of $x$ and $y$. Therefore, when computing the partial derivative with respect to one of the variables, the other variable is fixed and can be factored out of the derivative according to the rules of differentiation. The derivative is found using the rules for differentiating a power function of one variable. We have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& z_{x}^{\prime}=\left(x^{2} y^{3}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=y^{3}\left(x^{2}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=2 x y^{3} \\
& z_{y}^{\prime}=\left(x^{2} y^{3}\right)_{y}^{\prime}=x^{2}\left(y^{3}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=3 x^{2} y^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

2) This function is the sum of two functions of one variable. Therefore, when finding the partial derivative with respect to one of the variables, according to the rule for differentiating the sum of two functions, the partial derivative is equal to the sum of the derivatives of the functions with respect to the corresponding variable. The derivative of the function with the fixed variable is zero, as it is the derivative of a constant. Thus, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& z_{x}^{\prime}=\left(x^{5}+y^{6}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=\left(x^{5}\right)_{x}^{\prime}+\left(y^{6}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=5 x^{4}+0=5 x^{4} \\
& z_{y}^{\prime}=\left(x^{5}+y^{6}\right)_{y}^{\prime}=\left(x^{5}\right)_{y}^{\prime}+\left(y^{6}\right)_{y}^{\prime}=0+6 y^{5}=6 y^{5}
\end{aligned}
$$

3) This function is also the sum of two functions, but each of them is a function of two variables $x$ and $y$. When finding the partial derivatives of this function as the sum of partial derivatives, it is important to note that one of the functions is a power function, while the other is an exponential function. Thus, we have

$$
\begin{gathered}
z_{x}^{\prime}=\left(x^{y}\right)_{x}^{\prime}+\left(y^{x}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=y x^{y-1}+y^{x} \ln y \\
z_{x}^{\prime}=\left(x^{y}\right)_{y}^{\prime}+\left(y^{x}\right)_{y}^{\prime}=x \ln x-1+x y^{x-1}
\end{gathered}
$$

4) To find the partial derivatives of this function, it is most convenient to change the base using the formula $\log _{a} b=\frac{\log _{c} b}{\log _{c} a}$. We have $z=\log _{y} x=\frac{\ln x}{\ln y}$. Taking this into account, we get:

$$
\begin{gathered}
z_{x}^{\prime}=\left(\frac{\ln x}{\ln y}\right)_{x}^{\prime}=\left(\frac{1}{\ln y} \ln x\right)_{x}^{\prime}=\frac{1}{\ln y}(\ln x)_{x}^{\prime}=\frac{1}{x \ln y} \\
z_{y}^{\prime}=\left(\frac{\ln x}{\ln y}\right)_{y}^{\prime}=\ln x\left(\frac{1}{\ln y}\right)_{y}^{\prime}=\ln x\left((\ln y)^{-1}\right)_{y}^{\prime}= \\
=\ln x(-1)(\ln y)^{-2} \frac{1}{y}=-\frac{\ln x}{y \ln ^{2} y}
\end{gathered}
$$

